                     <!-- 
Notes
1. The liminal sign rendered by @ can probably be interpreted as siddham.
1. titaṁ: see note 1 in Boechari 1979, p. 21.
3. dalaṁña: this is evidence relevant for the general parameters of interpretation of anusvāra.
3. Note din drohaka where KB has diṁ drohaka (see note 6 Cœdès): this is evidence relevant for the general parameters of interpretation of anusvāra, and the use of homorganic nasal for anusvāra is probably a case of hypersanskritism.
4. Cœdès’ note 7 confuses the readings of KK (marpādaḥ) and KB (marppādaḥ). The photos available would allow reading tīda yaṁ tatvārjjava, but the apparent anusvāra may well be no more than a spot of damage on the stone.
5. Cœdès reads upuḥ tūva, and his note 4 on this reading contains a curious mistake. Instead of his tūva ipuḥ, one must presumably read ipuḥ tūva. OR HE HAS CONFUSED III AND IV.
6. Cœdès places the dot between sarāmvat· and kasīhan· in brackets, which means the sign would only be present in Karang Brahi. This is incorrect. Kota Kapur clearly displays it too.
7. sāraṁbhāña: this is evidence relevant for the general parameters of interpretation of anusvāra.
                     -->
               </listApp>
